'''Dorit Bar-On''' is a [[Professor]] of [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Connecticut]] and Director of the Expression, Communication, and the Origins of Meaning (ECOM) Research Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://philosophy.uconn.edu/faculty/|title=Faculty {{!}} Philosophy Department|website=philosophy.uconn.edu|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecomresearchgroup.com/members.html|title=ECOM Members|website=Expression, Communication, and the Origins of Meaning Research Group|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://leiterreports.typepad.com/blog/2013/03/bar-on-simmons-from-north-carolina-to-u-conn.html|title=Bar-On, Simmons from North Carolina to U Conn|website=Leiter Reports: A Philosophy Blog|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref> Her research focuses on [[philosophy of language]], [[philosophy of mind]], [[epistemology]], and [[Meta-ethics|metaethics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.doritbar-on.com/|title=Dorit Bar-On|website=Dorit Bar-On|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref> She previously held positions at the [[University of Rochester]] and [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|UNC-Chapel Hill]], where she was the Zachary Smith Distinguished Term Professor of Research and Undergraduate Education from 2014-2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://our.unc.edu/about/people/distinguished-professorships/|title=OUR Distinguished Professors {{!}} Office for Undergraduate Research {{!}} The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|website=our.unc.edu|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref>
== Education and career == Bar-On earned a BA (summa cum laude) at [[Tel Aviv University]] in Philosophy & [[Linguistics]] before earning her MA and PhD in Philosophy at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.doritbar-on.com/uploads/1/3/6/9/13698997/bar-oncv2015-16.pdf|title=Curriculum Vitae|last=Bar-On|first=Dorit|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref> Her dissertation, ''Indeterminacy of Translation: Theory and Practice'', was written under the supervision of [[Tyler Burge]], [[Rogers Albritton]], [[Keith Donnellan]], [[David Kaplan (philosopher)|David Kaplan]], and [[David Pears]]. Bar-On has also written Hebrew translations of poetry, fiction, and philosophy, including three anthologies in modern philosophy, writings by [[Iris Murdoch]], [[Kurt Vonnegut]], [[John Dos Passos|Dos Passos]], [[Dorothy Richardson]], [[E. E. Cummings]], [[Robert Louis Stevenson]], [[Walter Scott]], and, in collaboration with [[Marcia Falk]], a collection of poems by [[Zelda (poet)|Zelda Schneerson Mishkovsky]] and ''The Book of Blessings''.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Modern Trends in Philosophy, Vol.1|last=Kasher|first=Asa and Shalom Lapids (eds.), translated by Dorit Bar-On|publisher=Yachdav|year=1982|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Modern Trends in Philosophy, Vol. 2|last=Kasher|first=Asa, and Shalom Lapin (eds.), translated by Dorit Bar-On|publisher=Yachdav|year=1985|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Nice and the Good|last=Murdoch|first=Iris, translated by Dorit Bar-On|publisher=Zmora, Bitan, Modan|year=1982|isbn=|location=Tel Aviv|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Breakfast of Champions|last=Vonnegut|first=Kurt, translated by Dorit Bar-On|publisher=Zmora Bitan|year=1983|isbn=|location=Tel Aviv|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cummings, E. E.|last2=Bar-On, Dorit (translator)|year=1979|title=Translation of E. E. Cummings poems|journal=Achsav ("Now")|publisher=Tel-Aviv-Jerusalem Achsav|volume=39-40}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Pilgrimage|last=Richardson|first=Dorothy, translated by Dorit Bar-On|publisher=Achshav, Vol 37-38|year=1978|isbn=|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QuMbDbvzfYAC&pg=PR11&lpg=PR11&dq=marcia+falk+dorit+bar-on&source=bl&ots=SynTamisPt&sig=SWXj1YEPJx-0f6FtmrqZrFx8rvw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwimzNj6-t_PAhVoxlQKHWWjAFEQ6AEIMjAD#v=onepage&q=marcia%20falk%20dorit%20bar-on&f=false|title=Sefer Ha-berakhot|last=Falk|first=Marcia|date=1999-01-08|publisher=Beacon Press|isbn=9780807010174|language=en}}</ref>
Her other professional experience includes being a radio producer, editor and broadcaster for the Israel IDF radio station, a television writer and host in Israel, and a Hebrew television newscaster and interviewer for Channel 18 in Los Angeles.<ref name=":0" /> Bar-On also formerly served as the President of MYCO@UNC, a youth chamber organization, from 2009 to 2012.<ref name=":0" />
== Research == In ''Speaking My Mind: Expression and Self-Knowledge'', published by Oxford University Press, Bar-On investigates the problem of [[Know thyself|self-knowledge]] (how, if at all, we are each in a privileged position to know own [[mental state]]s) in relation to questions of expression and expressive behavior.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/speaking-my-mind-9780199276288?cc=us&lang=en&|title=Speaking My Mind: Expression and Self-Knowledge|last=Bar-On|first=Dorit|publisher=Oxford|year=2004|isbn=9780199276288|location=|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref><ref>Reviewed in {{Cite journal|last=Byrne|first=Alex|date=2011-11-01|title=Review Essay of Dorit Bar-On’s Speaking My Mind|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1933-1592.2011.00500.x/abstract|journal=Philosophy and Phenomenological Research|language=en|volume=83|issue=3|pages=705–717|doi=10.1111/j.1933-1592.2011.00500.x|issn=1933-1592}}</ref> She draws on historical figures including [[Ludwig Wittgenstein|Wittgenstein]] and [[Charles Darwin|Darwin]] to develop a neo-expressivist view of first-personal expressive utterances (such as, "I am in pain") which explains how these utterances differ epistemically from non-expressive utterances while sharing the same [[Semantics|semantic]] structure.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2016/entries/introspection/|title=Introspection|last=Schwitzgebel|first=Eric|date=|publisher=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|year=2014|isbn=|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|edition=Winter 2016|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref> ''Speaking My Mind'' has been praised as "a rich book; rich in topics, in argumentation, and in philosophical imagination and insight. It deserves the attention of all who work in mind and language."<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Owens|first=Joseph|date=2007-02-09|title=Review of Speaking My Mind: Expression and Self-Knowledge|url=http://ndpr.nd.edu/news/25212-speaking-my-mind-expression-and-self-knowledge/|issn=1538-1617}}</ref> In subsequent work, Bar-On has applied this neo-expressivist framework to additional problems in the philosophy of language, metaethics, and epistemology.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=Ra8VDAAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA133&dq=dorit+bar-on+ethical+neo-expressivism&ots=nCBwAPVfuv&sig=JutvnhPUECvIB14yrqcoce6p4fM#v=onepage&q&f=false|title="Ethical Neo-Expressivism", Oxford Studies in Metaethics: Volume Four (ed. Russ Shafer-Landau)|last=Bar-on|first=Dorit and Matthew Christman|date=2009-06-25|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=9780199566303|location=|pages=|language=en|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=“Externalism and Skepticism: Recognition, Expression, and Self-Knowledge”, Self-Knowledge and the Self, A. Coliva, ed., Oxford UP, 2011|last=Bar-On|first=Dorit|publisher=Oxford|year=2011|isbn=0415926904|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref> More recently, Bar-On has sought to illuminate the nature of human communication by situating it in relation to animal expressive communication more broadly, and thereby to show how human linguistic meaning can be understood consistently with a [[Naturalism (philosophy)|naturalistic]] theory of the world.<ref>{{Cite book|title="Triangulation and the Beasts." In Triangulation: from an Epistemological Point of View, C. Amoretti and G. Preyer (eds.).|last=Bar-On|first=Dorit and M. Priselac|publisher=Ontos Verlag|year=2011|isbn=3868381198|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Goldberg|first=Nathaniel|date=2011-10-17|title=Review of Triangulation: From an Epistemological Point of View|url=http://ndpr.nd.edu/news/26938-triangulation-from-an-epistemological-point-of-view/|issn=1538-1617}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecomresearchgroup.com/|title=ECOM Research Group Home Page|website=Expression, Communication, and the Origins of Meaning Research Group|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref>
