'''Joel J. Kupperman''' (born May 18, 1936) is a professor of philosophy at the [[University of Connecticut]] and author of ''[[Six Myths about the Good Life]]'', a popular philosophical volume centering on those values most worth engaging in human life. He is best known to the general public as a young math expert on the radio and television show ''[[Quiz Kids]]''. He astounded audiences with his ability to do complex mathematics rapidly and seemingly "in his head." He also had strong general knowledge, and was often the winner of the weekly competitions featured on the show. The 1944 film ''[[Chip Off the Old Block]]'' , starring [[Donald O'Connor]], [[Peggy Ryan]] and [[Ann Blyth]], featured Kupperman as the "Quiz Kid", representative of the group.<ref>Kupperman, Joel J. ''Six Myths about the Good Life: Thinking about what has Value''. [[Indianapolis]]: [[Hackett Publishing Company|Hackett]], [[2006 in literature|2006]]</ref>
During his initial ''Quiz Kids'' shows, Kupperman, who was then 7, lisped, which emphasized his youth and endeared him to the listening audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19830109&id=ip4cAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UGgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6968,4643405|title=Sarasota Herald-Tribune - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> In one episode of ''Quiz Kids'', Joel showed his ability to multiply any number times 99 "in his head." When asked how he was able to do this he replied "It's a theequit twick." When asked what the "secret trick" was, he explained that he merely multiplied the number he was given by one hundred, then subtracted the original number from that total to get the correct answer.
He received his bachelor's and master's degrees at the [[University of Chicago]], and his doctorate at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web2.uconn.edu/philosophy/department/kupperman/vjk.pdf|title=Joel J. Kupperman Curriculum Vitae|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> He started teaching at the University of Connecticut in 1960 and was made a full professor in 1972.
He is married to noted historian/author [[Karen Ordahl Kupperman]], who teaches at [[New York University]]. The couple have two children: [[Michael Kupperman|Michael Joel Kupperman]], a noted illustrator; and Charlie Anders Kupperman,<ref name="uconn.edu">[http://www.philosophy.uconn.edu/department/cogitamus/cogi4.html ]{{dead link|date=November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XJSdT_4NWTMC&pg=PA138&lpg=PA138&dq=karen+kupperman+bio+american+woman&source=bl&ots=SFNapG97TV&sig=M5wXBcKM3tFJQWVyLGvlKDKtV4s&hl=en&ei=DfyGTP24EIeksQOc0YCJCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CBcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=joel&f=false|title=American Women Historians, 1700s-1990s: A Biographical Dictionary|first1=Jennifer|last1=Scanlon|first2=Shaaron|last2=Cosner|date=19 November 1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|accessdate=19 November 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref> a medical journalist and editor for Eli Healthcare.<ref>[http://www.partbinsider.com/bios.htm]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elihealthcare.com/hc_staff.htm|title=Medical Coding & Billing Newsletters - Compliance & Reimbursement Alert|website=TheCodingInstitute|accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="uconn.edu"/>
In 2018 [[Simon & Schuster]] published ''All the Answers'', a graphic memoir by Michael Kupperman on his father Joel's rise to fame and his subsequent retreat from public life.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/All-The-Answers/Michael-Kupperman/9781501166433|title=All The Answers|date=2018-05-15|isbn=9781501166433|language=en}}</ref>
